Formosa, Qantas, Sun Hung Kai: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-09-15T21:40:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-15/formosa-qantas-sun-hung-kai-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Aquila Resources Ltd. (AQA)  : International Coal Ventures
Ltd. and Henan Coal Chemical Industry Group Co. are among
bidders for an Aquila coal mine in Australia, three people with
knowledge of the matter said. The companies are bidding for
Aquila’s Washpool coking coal project, said the people, who
declined to be identified because the talks are confidential.
Final bids due next month may value Washpool at as much as A$400
million ($413 million), one of the people said. Aquila climbed
6.7 percent to A$5.92.  Formosa Petrochemical Corp. (6505)  (6505 TT): Formosa named Chen
Bao-lang, a former president of state-run oil company CPC Corp.,
as its chairman, the refiner said in a statement to the Taiwan
stock exchange. Chen succeeds Wilfred Wang, who resigned after
fires at the company’s Mailiao plants in western Taiwan. Formosa
rose 2.4 percent to NT$82.20.  iPeople Inc. (IPO)  : The Manila-based provider of
educational services said second-quarter profit increased to
39.67 million pesos from 24.4 million pesos ($563,000) in the
same period a year ago, a stock-exchange filing showed. The
stock gained 0.2 percent to 4.37 pesos when it last traded Sept.
8.  MacroAsia Corp. (MAC)  : The Philippine provider of in-
flight catering services bought back 38,000 shares, a stock-
exchange filing showed. The stock decreased 0.3 percent to 3.32
pesos.  Qantas Airways Ltd. (QAN)  : Australia’s biggest airline
will use larger aircraft, consolidate services and deploy
management to limit the impact of planned  strike action  by
members of the Transport Workers Union on Sept. 20. The four-
hour strike will interrupt the morning peak at most airports and
the carrier will contact affected passengers, Sydney-based
Qantas said in an e-mailed statement. Qantas jumped 3.7 percent
to A$1.545.  SM Development Corp. (SMDC)  : The Manila-based property
company will start the construction next month of a 2 billion
peso residential tower project that will be completed in the
fourth quarter of 2014, a stock-exchange filing showed. The
stock increased 1.8 percent to 8.55 pesos.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK): The world’s biggest
developer by market value said full-year underlying profit rose
55 percent to a record high after home sales and rental income
increased. Profit excluding property revaluations rose to
HK$21.5 billion ($2.8 billion) for the 12 months ended June 30,
the Hong Kong-based builder said in a statement to the city’s
stock exchange. Sun Hung Kai gained 1.5 percent to HK$102.40.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
 anguyen@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net . 